  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I tell Google to deindex my all pages site?",
  "response": "To deindex all pages of your site from Google, you'll need to follow a series of steps. Here's a step-by-step guide on how to do this:\n\n1. **Verify Your Site in Google Search Console:**\n   Before you can request the removal of your site, you need to verify your ownership of the site in Google Search Console.\n\n   - Go to [Google Search Console](https://search.google.com/search-console).\n   - Click on \"Add Property\" and enter your site's URL.\n   - Follow the verification steps (you can choose from several methods like HTML tag, DNS record, or uploading an HTML file).\n\n2. **Remove URLs Using the \"Remove URLs\" Tool:**\n   Once your site is verified, you can use the \"Remove URLs\" tool to request the temporary removal of URLs.\n\n   - In Google Search Console, select your site.\n   - Navigate to \"Removals\" on the left-hand menu.\n   - Click \"New Request\".\n   - Choose \"Remove this URL only\" or \"Remove this URL and all URLs with this prefix\" depending on your needs. For removing all pages, use \"Remove this URL and all URLs with this prefix\".\n   - Enter the root domain of your site (e.g., `example.com`).\n   - Submit the request.\n\n3. **Block Googlebot Using `robots.txt`:**\n   While the \"Remove URLs\" tool provides temporary removal, to prevent Google from indexing your site in the future, you need to modify your `robots.txt` file.\n\n   - Create or edit your `robots.txt` file in the root directory of your site.\n   - Add the following lines to block all crawlers:\n\n     ```plaintext\n     User-agent: *\n     Disallow: /\n     ```\n\n   This tells all crawlers not to crawl any part of your site.\n\n4. **Submit a Sitemap with No URLs:**\n   If you have a sitemap submitted to Google, you should update it to contain no URLs or remove it entirely.\n\n   - In Google Search Console, go to \"Sitemaps\".\n   - If you have a sitemap listed, you can submit a new one that is empty or delete the existing sitemap.\n\n5. **Use Meta Robots Tag:**\n   To ensure that any remaining pages are not indexed, you can add a meta robots tag to your pages.\n\n   - Add the following tag to the `<head>` section of your HTML pages:\n\n     ```html\n     <meta name=\"robots\" content=\"noindex, nofollow\">\n     ```\n\n6. **Wait and Monitor:**\n   After completing these steps, it may take some time for Google to process your requests and update their index. Monitor your site's status in Google Search Console.\n\n   - Check the \"Coverage\" report to see if your site's pages are being removed from the index.\n   - You can also use the \"URL inspection\" tool to check the status of specific URLs.\n\n7. **Permanent Removal:**\n   If you want to ensure your site is permanently removed from Google's index, you may need to keep the `robots.txt` file and meta tags in place and continue to monitor Google Search Console.\n\nBy following these steps, you should be able to deindex all pages of your site from Google. Remember that while some of these steps provide immediate results, it may take time for Google to fully remove your site from their index.",
